        "materials_required": [
            "19mm (3/4\") boards (ply or MDF)",
            "60mm dowel for the face buttons",
            "Wood stain, varnish and thinners",
            "Arduino Leonardo/Pro Micro with USB HID joystick profile",
            "Microswitch buttons",
            "Mini breadboard",
            "Connecting wires (Dupont jumper wires)",
            "Electronics solder",
            "Heat shrink tubing",
            "Glue (Glu Dots or a glue gun)"
        ],
        "description": "This project describes how to build a giant, functional retro gamepad, inspired by the NES and SNES controllers, using scrap wood and inexpensive electronics. It connects via USB and emulates a standard HID joystick, making it compatible with various platforms.",
        "steps": [
            "Cut the D-Pad button from laminated board, sand it, and round the edges using a router.",
            "Trace the D-Pad button on the top board and cut out the D-Pad shaped hole.",
            "Cut the face buttons from the 60mm dowel and the smaller pill shaped buttons for Start and Select from offcuts from the top board.",
            "Cut equivalent holes in the top board using the 60mm hole saw for the larger buttons and the 25mm hole saw and the jigsaw for the start and select buttons.",
            "Round off the top edges of the face buttons using a router.",
            "Round off the corners on the top board using the jigsaw and add a beveled edge all around using the router with the chamfer bit.",
            "Cut the base board to shape, making it slightly larger than the top board.",
            "Round both top and bottom edges of the base board using the router.",
            "Stain/varnish the buttons with a dark Polyurethane based stain/varnish.",
            "Stain the base board using a dark wood stain.",
            "Finish the top and bottom boards with clear satin varnish, using multiple coats and rubbing down with steel wool and thinners in between coats.",
            "Cut a cavity in the base board for the electronics using a router.",
            "Cut wiring ducts to all of the buttons using a router.",
            "Cut a cavity into the rear of the top board to allow extra space for the micro-controller and breadboard.",
            "Wire micro-switches in parallel for each button to the breadboard.",
            "Wire the controller using the mini-breadboard and Dupont connectors to the Arduino.",
            "Upload the Arduino Joystick Library code to the Arduino.",
            "Attach the micro-switches to the base board using glue.",
            "Make feet using the hole saw cutouts from the face button holes and bevel their bottom edge using the router.",
            "Screw the base and top boards together through the feet.",
            "Drill holes in the base board at the button centres so that a screw could be loosely slotted through and then screwed into the button.",
            "Add extra micro-switches to avoid the button getting pushed into a dead space and getting stuck.",
            "Add pieces of spring so that the buttons wouldn't move around."
        ]
    }
